## Pass 1: Initial Performance Review

### Summary Assessment

This code has **numerous per-call allocation hotspots** that will generate severe GC pressure at millions of calls/minute. The critical issues are: repeated `string.ToLowerInvariant()` and string interpolation in `FormatTimePart`, LINQ chains that allocate multiple enumerators and intermediate collections, and a `params` array allocation on every `Transform` call.

### Root Cause

Nearly every method in this file creates transient heap objects (lists, enumerator state machines, intermediate arrays, interpolated strings) on every invocation. None of the results that are constant or derivable from a small enum are cached. At millions of calls/minute, these micro-allocations compound into continuous Gen0 GC pauses that kill throughput and tail latency.

---

### Recommended Changes

#### 🔴 1. `FormatTimePart` — `ToLowerInvariant()` + string interpolation on every call

This is the single hottest allocation site. Called once per non-zero time unit per `Humanize` call.

```csharp
// ❌ Allocates: ToString() string, ToLowerInvariant() string, interpolated string — EVERY call
private static string FormatTimePart(int value, TimeUnit unit, CultureInfo culture)
{
    var unitName = unit.ToString().ToLowerInvariant();
    return value == 1 ? $"{value} {unitName}" : $"{value} {unitName}s";
}
```

```csharp
// ✅ Cache unit names; use string.Create or string.Concat to avoid interpolation overhead
private static readonly string[] UnitNamesSingular = BuildUnitNames(plural: false);
private static readonly string[] UnitNamesPlural = BuildUnitNames(plural: true);

private static string[] BuildUnitNames(bool plural)
{
    var values = Enum.GetValues<TimeUnit>();
    var names = new string[values.Length];
    foreach (var unit in values)
    {
        var lower = unit.ToString().ToLowerInvariant();
        names[(int)unit] = plural ? lower + "s" : lower;
    }
    return names;
}

private static string FormatTimePart(int value, TimeUnit unit, CultureInfo culture)
{
    var unitName = value == 1 ? UnitNamesSingular[(int)unit] : UnitNamesPlural[(int)unit];
    return string.Concat(value.ToString(CultureInfo.InvariantCulture), " ", unitName);
}
```

**Expected impact:** Eliminates 2–3 string allocations per time part. At 5 units × millions of calls, this is the largest single win.

**Trade-off:** Slightly more setup code; negligible complexity increase.

---

#### 🔴 2. `SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan` — LINQ chains + list materialization

```csharp
// ❌ Up to 3 lazy LINQ enumerators + [.. timeParts] allocates a new List<string?>
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    IEnumerable<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    if (!countEmptyUnits)
        timeParts = timeParts.Where(x => x != null);
    timeParts = timeParts.Take(precision);
    if (countEmptyUnits)
        timeParts = timeParts.Where(x => x != null);
    return [.. timeParts];
}
```

```csharp
// ✅ Single-pass loop over the already-allocated List<string?>. Mutate in place.
private static void SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    List<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    int kept = 0;
    int writeIndex = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < timeParts.Count; i++)
    {
        bool isNonNull = timeParts[i] != null;
        bool counts = countEmptyUnits || isNonNull;

        if (counts)
        {
            if (kept >= precision) break;
            kept++;
        }

        if (isNonNull)
        {
            timeParts[writeIndex++] = timeParts[i];
        }
    }

    // Trim the list to only the kept items
    if (writeIndex < timeParts.Count)
        timeParts.RemoveRange(writeIndex, timeParts.Count - writeIndex);
}
```

**Expected impact:** Eliminates 3 enumerator allocations + 1 `List<string?>` allocation per call. The existing `List<string?>` from `CreateTimeParts` is reused.

---

#### 🔴 3. `ConcatenateTimeSpanParts` — `.Where().ToList()` + `string.Join` with LINQ `.Take()`

```csharp
// ❌ Allocates: Where enumerator, new List<string?>, Take enumerator, interpolated string
var parts = timeSpanParts.Where(x => x != null).ToList();
// ...
var allButLast = string.Join(collectionSeparator, parts.Take(parts.Count - 1));
return $"{allButLast} and {parts[^1]}";
```

```csharp
// ✅ After SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan filters in-place, the list already has only non-null items.
// Accept List<string?> directly, use span-friendly join.
private static string ConcatenateTimeSpanParts(
    List<string?> parts, CultureInfo culture, string collectionSeparator)
{
    if (parts.Count == 0)
        return "no time";

    if (parts.Count == 1)
        return parts[0]!;

    // Use CollectionsMarshal to get span and avoid Take() enumerator
    var span = System.Runtime.InteropServices.CollectionsMarshal.AsSpan(parts);
    var allButLast = string.Join(collectionSeparator, span[..^1].ToArray());
    return string.Concat(allButLast, " and ", parts[^1]);
}
```

Alternatively, for maximum throughput, build with a `ValueStringBuilder` or `DefaultInterpolatedStringHandler` to avoid intermediate `string.Join` allocations — but the above already removes the LINQ overhead.

**Expected impact:** Eliminates `Where` enumerator + `ToList` + `Take` enumerator. `string.Concat(3 args)` avoids the `FormattableString` boxing that `$""` can cause in some code paths.

---

#### 🟡 4. `IsContainingOnlyNullValue` — LINQ `Any()` on a `List<string?>`

```csharp
// ❌ Allocates an enumerator + delegate for .Any() on a List<string?>
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(IEnumerable<string?> timeParts) =>
    !timeParts.Any(x => x != null);
```

```csharp
// ✅ Accept List<string?>, use a simple loop — zero allocation
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(List<string?> timeParts)
{
    for (int i = 0; i < timeParts.Count; i++)
    {
        if (timeParts[i] != null) return false;
    }
    return true;
}
```

**Expected impact:** Eliminates 1 enumerator allocation per call. Small per-call saving, but it's on the hot path.

---

#### 🟡 5. `CreateTimePartsWithNoTimeValue` — allocation in the "no time" path

```csharp
// ❌ Allocates a new List<string?> just to return one element, then indexes [0]
return CreateTimePartsWithNoTimeValue("no time")[0] ?? "no time";
```

```csharp
// ✅ Return the string directly — no list needed
if (IsContainingOnlyNullValue(timeParts))
{
    return "no time";
}
```

The `CreateTimePartsWithNoTimeValue` method can be removed entirely.

---

#### 🟡 6. `TimeUnits` static field — `Enumerable.Reverse(Enum.GetValues<>())`

This only runs once at startup, so it's not a throughput issue, but worth cleaning up:

```csharp
// ❌ Enumerable.Reverse allocates a buffer + iterator
private static readonly TimeUnit[] TimeUnits = [.. Enumerable.Reverse(Enum.GetValues<TimeUnit>())];
```

```csharp
// ✅ Literal reversed array — zero runtime overhead
private static readonly TimeUnit[] TimeUnits =
[
    TimeUnit.Millisecond, TimeUnit.Second, TimeUnit.Minute, TimeUnit.Hour,
    TimeUnit.Day, TimeUnit.Week, TimeUnit.Month, TimeUnit.Year
];
```

**Expected impact:** Marginal (startup only), but it's free correctness and removes a fragile dependency on enum ordering.

---

#### 🟡 7. `TransformExtensions.Transform` — `params` array + `Aggregate` LINQ

```csharp
// ❌ params allocates a new IStringTransformer[] on every call site;
// Aggregate allocates an enumerator + delegate
public static string Transform(
    this string input, CultureInfo culture, params IStringTransformer[] transformers) =>
    transformers.Aggregate(input, (current, t) => t.Transform(current));
```

```csharp
// ✅ Add a 1-arg overload for the most common case (single transformer)
public static string Transform(
    this string input, CultureInfo culture, IStringTransformer transformer) =>
    transformer.Transform(input);

// Keep the params version for 2+ transformers, but replace Aggregate with a loop
public static string Transform(
    this string input, CultureInfo culture, params IStringTransformer[] transformers)
{
    for (int i = 0; i < transformers.Length; i++)
        input = transformers[i].Transform(input);
    return input;
}
```

If on .NET 8+, also consider `params ReadOnlySpan<IStringTransformer>` to eliminate the array entirely for 2-3 arg call sites.

**Expected impact:** Single-transformer calls (common case) drop from 1 array + 1 enumerator + 1 delegate to zero allocations.

---

#### 🟡 8. `HumanizeDisplayStrings` — `.Select().Where().ToArray()` chain

```csharp
// ❌ Select enumerator + Where enumerator + intermediate array
var itemsArray = strings
    .Select(item => item == null ? string.Empty : item.Trim())
    .Where(item => !string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(item))
    .ToArray();
```

```csharp
// ✅ Single-pass build into a reusable list (or stackalloc + ArrayPool for small collections)
private string HumanizeDisplayStrings(IEnumerable<string?> strings, string separator)
{
    // Use a local list to avoid repeated allocations in a tight loop.
    // For an even lower-alloc approach, use ArrayPool<string>.
    var items = new List<string>();
    foreach (var item in strings)
    {
        if (item == null) continue;
        var trimmed = item.AsSpan().Trim();
        if (trimmed.IsEmpty) continue;
        // Only allocate the trimmed string if it's different from the original
        items.Add(trimmed.Length == item.Length ? item : trimmed.ToString());
    }

    return items.Count switch
    {
        0 => string.Empty,
        1 => items[0],
        _ => string.Concat(
                 string.Join(separator, items.Take(items.Count - 1)),
                 " and ",
                 items[^1])
    };
}
```

**Expected impact:** Eliminates 2 enumerator allocations. The `Trim()` optimization avoids allocating a new string when the original wasn't padded.

